  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Prayer Blessing for the Sovereign
  author: Seok Bok-am
  language: eng
  text: 'Compassion that benefits all beings in the dusty world—this is the unity of self and other. Our humble prayers for our lord beneath the forest eaves spring from a single, undivided heart. How much more so, having received the grace of royal provision, do we redouble our blessings upon your longevity and splendor. This mountain monastery where practitioners dwell is the very wellspring of our ancestors'' teachings. Though we strive to keep the Dharma wheel ever turning, our scanty portions leave the alms bowl too often bare—a worry shared by all. Yet the sovereign, in gracious compassion, deigns to gaze upon our plight, and sends forth a month''s sustenance like heaven''s rain and dew. No longer need we sustain each other with mere fragments, but rather the cicada''s throat shall drink deep of plenty. From the sixteenth day of the first moon through the fifteenth of the second, we establish a special observance, practicing the sacred rites with utmost devotion. May this sincere offering touch the perfectly luminous mirror of the Buddha''s wisdom. We humbly pray: May heaven''s blessing be upon you, and may the royal reign extend through ten thousand ages; may the emperor''s favor endure, and warfare cease in all four quarters; may the queen and young prince dwell in peace, and all the royal kindred live in harmony together.'
  footnotes:
    - The 'dusty world' (塵中) refers to the realm of worldly affairs and politics, contrasted with the 'forest' (林下) of monastic practice.
    - The 'alms bowl' (鉢) and references to 'fish foam' (魚沫) and 'cicada's throat' (蟬腸) are poetic expressions for scarcity and sufficiency of sustenance in monastic life.
    - This prayer was composed as part of a formal observance lasting one lunar month, during which special Buddhist rituals were performed to invoke blessings upon the sovereign.
